When a small group of organisms (a small population) breaks away from the main population from which they originated (say, by moving across a river or mountain range, or when such organisms migrate to a new island, making it difficult for them to return), they often find themselves in an environment that is significantly different from the one they came from.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so in order to become a strong competitor itself, the new population will need different traits or adaptations compared to those it had before.
The original population has not changed at all: as before, it still needs to adapt.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, the animals become less and less like the main population from which they split.
Thousands or even millions of years will pass, and sooner or later the two populations in question will look so different that no one will even think of classifying them as the same species.
We call this process speciation, which actually means the emergence of new species. Speciation is an inevitable result and a very important stage of evolution.
